# Deferred Task Tracking Rule

**Status:** MANDATORY
**Owner:** All AI Assistants (Composer, Codex, GPT-5, External Agents)

---

## Rule: Deferred Tasks Must Be Marked with [D] and Cross-Referenced

**MANDATORY:** When a task is deferred (not completed in the current phase but intentionally moved to a future phase), you MUST:

1. Mark the task with `[D]` instead of `[x]` or `[ ]`
2. Include the target phase ID where the work will be done
3. Add a corresponding entry in the target phase that references the deferred item

**This ensures:**
- Deferred work is explicitly tracked (not lost)
- Future phases know what work was deferred to them
- Phase completion gates can distinguish between "not done" and "intentionally deferred"

---

## Format

### In Source Phase (Where Task is Deferred)

```markdown
- [D] Task description (deferred to Phase X.Y.Z)
```

**Example:**
```markdown
- [D] Feature integration (deferred to Phase 2.3)
- [D] Advanced optimization (deferred to Phase 3.1 - requires profiling)
- [D] Performance tuning (deferred to Phase 4.2 - requires benchmarks)
```

### In Target Phase (Where Work Will Be Done)

Add a section or checklist item that references the deferred work:

```markdown
#### Deferred Work from Previous Phases

- [ ] Phase 2.1 deferred: Feature integration
- [ ] Phase 2.1 deferred: Advanced optimization (requires profiling)
- [ ] Phase 2.1 deferred: Performance tuning (requires benchmarks)
```

**Or inline in the phase tasks:**
```markdown
- [ ] Feature integration (Phase 2.1 deferred item)
- [ ] Advanced optimization (Phase 2.1 deferred - requires profiling)
```

---

## When to Use [D] vs [x] vs [ ]

- **`[x]`** - Task is complete and verified
- **`[D]`** - Task is intentionally deferred to a future phase (with phase reference)
- **`[ ]`** - Task is not yet done but should be done in this phase (incomplete work)

**CRITICAL:** Never use `[D]` without:
- A target phase ID
- A corresponding entry in the target phase

---

## Phase Completion Gate Behavior

The phase completion gate should:
- Count `[D]` items as "handled" (not incomplete)
- Verify that `[D]` items have target phase references
- Optionally verify that target phases have corresponding entries (future enhancement)

**Current behavior:** Phase completion gate counts `[D]` as incomplete. This rule defines the standard; gate script should be updated to handle `[D]` markers.

---

## Examples

### ✅ Good: Properly Deferred Task

**Phase 2.1:**
```markdown
- [D] Feature integration (deferred to Phase 2.3)
```

**Phase 2.3:**
```markdown
#### Integration Features

- [ ] Feature integration (Phase 2.1 deferred item)
  - [ ] Add integration method
  - [ ] Create adapter
  - [ ] Update router
```

### ❌ Bad: Deferred Without Reference

**Phase 2.1:**
```markdown
- [D] Feature integration
```

**Why bad:** No target phase specified, no way to track where this work will be done.

### ❌ Bad: Deferred Without Target Phase Entry

**Phase 2.1:**
```markdown
- [D] Feature integration (deferred to Phase 2.3)
```

**Phase 2.3:** (no mention of the deferred item)

**Why bad:** Target phase doesn't know about the deferred work.

---

## Integration with Other Rules

This rule works alongside:
- **Sequential Phase Enforcement:** Deferred items must reference valid future phases
- **Phase Completion Protocol:** `[D]` items are "handled" for completion purposes
- **Action Log Requirement:** Deferrals should be logged with rationale

---

## Enforcement

**MANDATORY:** This rule applies to ALL phases and tasks.

**Verification Checklist:**
- [ ] All `[D]` items have target phase references
- [ ] All target phases have corresponding entries for deferred work
- [ ] Deferral rationale is documented (why deferred, what's needed)

